input: What are the free models available on the bytez AI API in 2025?
output:
Based on my research, here's what I found about Bytez AI API's free offerings in 2025:

## Free Credits Program

Bytez operates primarily on a **usage-based model** with generous free credit programs rather than permanently free models:

- **$200,000 in free inference credits** - Being distributed to help build AI startups
- **Up to $100K credits per startup** - Available through their startup grant application program
- Credits apply to **both open and closed source models**, including premium providers like Anthropic, OpenAI, and others

## What You Get Access To

With these free credits, you can access:
- **220,000+ AI models** through one unified API key
- Latest open-source models (Llama 3, Mistral, DeepSeek, Qwen, Flux, etc.)
- Closed-source models (Claude 4.5, OpenAI, etc.)
- Multi-modal models (chat, image-to-text, audio-to-text, video-to-text)

## Getting Started

To access free credits, you need to:
1. Apply for their startup grant program at bytez.com
2. Get your API key from the Bytez Settings Page
3. Start using the credits across any of their 220,000+ models

**Note**: Bytez doesn't appear to have permanently "free" models. Instead, they offer substantial free credits that make experimentation and initial development effectively free for startups and developers.

Sources:
- [Bytez - open source AI](https://bytez.com/models)
- [GitHub - Bytez-com/docs](https://github.com/Bytez-com/docs)
- [AI Model API: 5 Reasons Bytez.com is the "Spotify" of Open Source AI - Informatra](https://www.informatra.com/ai-model-api-bytez-review/)
- [Bytez startup credits announcement on X](https://x.com/Bytez/status/1953583746562900403)
- [One Key, 175k+ Models: Mastering AI in Laravel with Bytez](https://medium.com/@martinlechene/one-key-175k-models-mastering-ai-in-laravel-with-bytez-7bc84d9083e8)

input: Can you show me a github example of a workers-rs wrangler.toml main entry point for 2026?
output:
Based on the search results, here's a current example of a `wrangler.toml` configuration for workers-rs (Rust-based Cloudflare Workers) in 2026:

```toml
name = "my-worker"
main = "./shim.mjs"
compatibility_date = "2026-01-29"

[build]
command = "cargo install -q worker-build && worker-build --release"

[build.upload]
dir = "build/worker"
format = "modules"
main = "./shim.mjs"

[[build.upload.rules]]
globs = ["**/*.wasm"]
type = "CompiledWasm"
```

Key points about the main entry point:

- **`main = "./shim.mjs"`** - This JavaScript shim file is automatically generated by the `worker-build` tool and serves as the entry point that loads your Rust WebAssembly module
- **`format = "modules"`** - Uses the ES modules format (required for Rust workers)
- **`dir = "build/worker"`** - The directory where the built artifacts are placed
- **Custom build command** - The build process uses `worker-build` to compile your Rust code to WebAssembly and generate the necessary shim

Your actual Rust code lives in `src/lib.rs`, and the build tooling handles creating the JavaScript entry point that bridges to your compiled Wasm module.

Sources:
- [GitHub - cloudflare/workers-rs: Write Cloudflare Workers in 100% Rust via WebAssembly](https://github.com/cloudflare/workers-rs)
- [rustwasm-worker-template/wrangler.toml at master · cloudflare/rustwasm-worker-template](https://github.com/cloudflare/rustwasm-worker-template/blob/master/wrangler.toml)
- [Configuration - Wrangler · Cloudflare Workers docs](https://developers.cloudflare.com/workers/wrangler/configuration/)
- [Cloudflare Workers — Rust language support · Cloudflare Workers docs](https://developers.cloudflare.com/workers/languages/rust/)
